{"id":5576,"date":"2015-05-07T07:00:11","date_gmt":"2015-05-07T13:00:11","guid":{"rendered":"http:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/?p=5576"},"modified":"2019-04-16T17:23:28","modified_gmt":"2019-04-16T23:23:28","slug":"taking-indoor-succulents-outside-for-the-summer","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/taking-indoor-succulents-outside-for-the-summer\/","title":{"rendered":"Taking indoor succulents outside for the summer"},"content":{"rendered":"<p><div class=\"fusion-fullwidth fullwidth-box fusion-builder-row-1 nonhundred-percent-fullwidth non-hundred-percent-height-scrolling\" style=\"background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0);background-position: center center;background-repeat: no-repeat;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;margin-bottom: 0px;margin-top: 0px;border-width: 0px 0px 0px 0px;border-color:#eae9e9;border-style:solid;\" ><div class=\"fusion-builder-row fusion-row\"><div class=\"fusion-layout-column fusion_builder_column fusion-builder-column-0 fusion_builder_column_1_1 1_1 fusion-one-full fusion-column-first fusion-column-last\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-column-wrapper fusion-flex-column-wrapper-legacy\" style=\"background-position:left top;background-repeat:no-repeat;-webkit-background-size:cover;-moz-background-size:cover;-o-background-size:cover;background-size:cover;padding: 0px 0px 0px 0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-1\"><p><em>Learn how to successfully move your indoor succulents outside when the weather warms up! Indoor succulents will benefit from the outside air and extra sun!<\/em><\/p>\n<p>You may have noticed that succulents growing outdoors often seem to be healthier and prettier than those grown indoors. The two biggest reasons for this are more sunlight (which\u00a0<a href=\"\/stretched-out-succulents\/\">prevents stretching<\/a>) and better airflow (allowing the roots to <a href=\"\/best-soil-for-succulents\/\">dry out more quickly<\/a>).<\/p>\n<h4>I highly recommend taking\u00a0your indoor succulents outside for the summer, at least for a little while.<\/h4>\n<p>As you do so however, there are a few things to keep in mind.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5790 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Indoor-succulents-will-benefit-from-being-outdoors-in-the-summer.jpg\" alt=\"Indoor succulents will benefit from being outdoors in the summer!\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Indoor-succulents-will-benefit-from-being-outdoors-in-the-summer-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Indoor-succulents-will-benefit-from-being-outdoors-in-the-summer-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Indoor-succulents-will-benefit-from-being-outdoors-in-the-summer.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<h3>Ease them into the sunlight and heat<\/h3>\n<p>Since there is much more sunlight outdoors it's very easy to burn your succulents with too much sunlight or <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/how-much-heat-can-succulents-handle\/\">too much heat<\/a>. Start your succulents in an area that gets full shade and gradually move them into an area with more sunlight.<\/p>\n<p>Succulents that are larger and have a more established root system will tolerate more light and heat more easily. On the other hand, newly planted succulents will need to be kept in the shade longer.<\/p>\n<p>Try adding an hour or two of sunlight each week. Morning sun is cooler and is best for succulents.<\/p>\n<p>[clickToTweet tweet=&#8221;Take your indoor succulents out for the summer, placing them in shade, gradually moving to full sun.&#8221; quote=&#8221;Take your indoor succulents out for the summer, placing them in shade, gradually moving to full sun.&#8221;]<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5784 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Discover-some-great-tips-for-moving-your-succulents-outdoors-for-the-summer.jpg\" alt=\"Discover some great tips for moving your succulents outdoors for the summer\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Discover-some-great-tips-for-moving-your-succulents-outdoors-for-the-summer-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Discover-some-great-tips-for-moving-your-succulents-outdoors-for-the-summer-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Discover-some-great-tips-for-moving-your-succulents-outdoors-for-the-summer.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Make sure you know there is actually shade all day! I burned a bunch of plants when I moved mine out this year. I have\u00a0a <a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B004BDP674\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B004BDP674&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=4LUHKNEJWSCFO7GA\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">wire rack<\/a>\u00a0on the east side of my house\u00a0where I generally keep my succulents. The roof hangs over the rack so I assumed it was shaded most of the day.<\/p>\n<p>While I knew it got some morning sun, I didn't realize it gets full sun until about 1:00 PM. This was way too much sun for most of my plants, especially\u00a0the leaves I was <a href=\"\/propagating-succulents\/\">propagating<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5785 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Dont-leave-your-succulent-leaves-out-in-direct-sun-or-theyll-burn.jpg\" alt=\"Don't leave your succulent leaves out in direct sun or they'll burn!\" width=\"735\" height=\"490\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Dont-leave-your-succulent-leaves-out-in-direct-sun-or-theyll-burn-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Dont-leave-your-succulent-leaves-out-in-direct-sun-or-theyll-burn-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Dont-leave-your-succulent-leaves-out-in-direct-sun-or-theyll-burn.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>So, learn from my mistake and keep them completely in the shade for a few days while they get used the extra light and warmer temperatures. After a few days in full shade move them to an area that gets morning sun. Wait a few more days and then move them to their permanent home.<\/p>\n<p>Watch for early signs of sunburn such as bleaching or extreme color change. If you see these signs, move your succulents back to an area with more shade.<\/p>\n<h3>Fertilize<\/h3>\n<p>Spring is a great time to fertilize succulents. Most are coming out of dormancy and are ready to grow. A little food will help them regain their color and produce healthy new offshoots!<\/p>\n<p>I recommend using <a href=\"http:\/\/ahavenbrand.com\/\" target=\"_blank\">Haven Manuere Tea<\/a>. This stuff is great! I did a post about <a href=\"\/learn-how-to-fertilize-succulents\/\" rel=\"noopener\">my experience with manure tea<\/a> with some before and after images.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-6624 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/11\/This-manure-tea-is-the-best-fertilizer-Ive-found-for-succulents-and-other-plants.jpg\" alt=\"This manure tea is the best fertilizer I've found for succulents and other plants!\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/11\/This-manure-tea-is-the-best-fertilizer-Ive-found-for-succulents-and-other-plants-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/11\/This-manure-tea-is-the-best-fertilizer-Ive-found-for-succulents-and-other-plants-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2015\/11\/This-manure-tea-is-the-best-fertilizer-Ive-found-for-succulents-and-other-plants.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<h3>Use Pot Feet<\/h3>\n<p>Rather than placing your pots directly on the ground, make sure to use <a href=\"https:\/\/www.amazon.com\/gp\/product\/B003BNRBF0\/ref=as_li_tl?ie=UTF8&camp=1789&creative=390957&creativeASIN=B003BNRBF0&linkCode=as2&tag=cassituttlpho-20&linkId=SAM2YG5FNI7RCMEJ\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">pot feet<\/a> or place them on something like my wire rack to allow for water drainage and airflow. Check out my post on <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/use-pot-feet-for-succulent-container-gardens\/\" rel=\"noopener\">using pot feet<\/a> for more details!<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5787 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Use-pot-feet-under-your-outdoor-succulent-containers-to-prevent-rot.jpg\" alt=\"Use pot feet under your outdoor succulent containers to prevent rot\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Use-pot-feet-under-your-outdoor-succulent-containers-to-prevent-rot-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Use-pot-feet-under-your-outdoor-succulent-containers-to-prevent-rot-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Use-pot-feet-under-your-outdoor-succulent-containers-to-prevent-rot.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<h3>Propagate<\/h3>\n<p>It's quite likely your succulents have really <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/stretched-out-succulents\/\">stretched<\/a> out over the winter. <a href=\"http:\/\/mountaincrestgardens.com\/echeveria\/?afmc=MCGSUNSHINE\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Echeverias<\/a> seem to get especially stretched out while <a href=\"https:\/\/www.awin1.com\/cread.php?awinaffid=233213&awinmid=6220&clickref=summer_aloe&p=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.etsy.com%2Flisting%2F159485566%2Fsucculent-plant-aloe-hybrid-firebird%3Fref%3Dshop_home_active_1%26ga_search_query%3Daloe\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">Aloes<\/a>\u00a0tend to keep their shape better. Now is a great time to chop of the top of the succulent and propagate it!<\/p>\n<p>For more details about propagating, check out <a href=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/propagating-succulents-the-ebook\/\" rel=\"noopener\">my ebook<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5788 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Beginning-of-spring-is-a-great-time-to-propagate-succulents.jpg\" alt=\"Beginning of spring is a great time to propagate succulents\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Beginning-of-spring-is-a-great-time-to-propagate-succulents-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Beginning-of-spring-is-a-great-time-to-propagate-succulents-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Beginning-of-spring-is-a-great-time-to-propagate-succulents.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<h3>Repot if necessary<\/h3>\n<p>If your succulent grew much larger over the winter, or if some plants sharing the same pot died, you'll likely want to repot your plants. Dump out the old soil, remove as much soil from the roots as you can. Clean out the pots with soapy water (then rinse out) or spray with isopropyl alcohol, and replant them with fresh <a href=\"https:\/\/www.bonsaijack.com\/Succulent_Soil_sas.html\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener nofollow sponsored\">new soil<\/a>!<\/p>\n<p>If your succulents have been growing in the same pot for a while they'll also appreciate the new soil and clean home. It's always nice to have freshly potted succulents for the summer.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5789 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Repot-your-succulents-at-the-beginning-of-spring-to-keep-them-healthy.jpg\" alt=\"Repot your succulents at the beginning of spring to keep them healthy\" width=\"735\" height=\"1103\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Repot-your-succulents-at-the-beginning-of-spring-to-keep-them-healthy-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Repot-your-succulents-at-the-beginning-of-spring-to-keep-them-healthy-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Repot-your-succulents-at-the-beginning-of-spring-to-keep-them-healthy.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<h3>Watch for bugs<\/h3>\n<p>Mealybugs love quickly growing plants. Keep an eye out for these nasty bugs after you move your plants out. Ants tend to spread mealybugs from plant to plant.<\/p>\n<p>If you do see mealybugs, kill them by pouring alcohol on them. You can see my full tutorial for <a href=\"\/kill-mealybugs-on-succulents\/\">combating mealybugs here<\/a>.<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5791 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Watch-out-for-mealybugs-on-your-indoor-succulents.jpg\" alt=\"Watch out for mealybugs on your indoor succulents!\" width=\"735\" height=\"490\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Watch-out-for-mealybugs-on-your-indoor-succulents-500x333.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Watch-out-for-mealybugs-on-your-indoor-succulents-700x467.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Watch-out-for-mealybugs-on-your-indoor-succulents.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>You may also notice other critters start to find your plants. Snails and slugs love succulents and will completely destroy them if given the chance. Squirrels, raccoons, birds, dogs and cats seem to enjoy playing with succulents as well. The bigger animals can be hard to deter and may force you to bring your plants back in. Any outdoor time is better than none though!<\/p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-5792 size-full\" src=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-how-to-keep-your-indoor-succulents-healthy-over-the-summer.jpg\" alt=\"Learn how to keep your indoor succulents healthy over the summer!\" width=\"735\" height=\"1102\" srcset=\"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-how-to-keep-your-indoor-succulents-healthy-over-the-summer-500x750.jpg 500w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-how-to-keep-your-indoor-succulents-healthy-over-the-summer-700x1050.jpg 700w, https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-content\/uploads\/2115\/05\/Learn-how-to-keep-your-indoor-succulents-healthy-over-the-summer.jpg 735w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 735px) 100vw, 735px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>As you are bringing your plants out for the summer, keep these things in mind. I can tell you from experience it's sad and frustrating to kill off plants from not paying attention to their needs.<\/p>\n<h4>Your plants will really benefit from the fresh air and a little more sunlight, so it's worth moving them out!<\/h4>\n<p>Be sure to keep them out of full sun for a while, fertilize, propagate, repot if necessary\u00a0and watch out for bugs and pests!<\/p>\n<\/div><div class=\"fusion-clearfix\"><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><div class=\"fusion-fullwidth fullwidth-box fusion-builder-row-2 nonhundred-percent-fullwidth non-hundred-percent-height-scrolling\" style=\"background-color: rgba(255,255,255,0);background-position: center center;background-repeat: no-repeat;padding-top:0px;padding-right:0px;padding-bottom:0px;padding-left:0px;margin-bottom: 0px;margin-top: 0px;border-width: 0px 0px 0px 0px;border-color:#eae9e9;border-style:solid;\" ><div class=\"fusion-builder-row fusion-row\"><div class=\"fusion-layout-column fusion_builder_column fusion-builder-column-1 fusion_builder_column_1_1 1_1 fusion-one-full fusion-column-first fusion-column-last\" style=\"margin-top:0px;margin-bottom:0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-column-wrapper fusion-flex-column-wrapper-legacy\" style=\"background-position:left top;background-repeat:no-repeat;-webkit-background-size:cover;-moz-background-size:cover;-o-background-size:cover;background-size:cover;padding: 0px 0px 0px 0px;\"><div class=\"fusion-text fusion-text-2\"><p><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\">.<\/span><\/p>\n<\/div><div class=\"fusion-clearfix\"><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/div><\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"","protected":false},"author":7,"featured_media":27466,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":[],"categories":[52,1],"tags":[119,81],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/5576"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/7"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=5576"}],"version-history":[{"count":0,"href":"https:\/\/www.succulentsandsunshine.com\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/5576\/revisions"}],